WEBVTT

00:11.480 --> 00:13.680
You better have
a hell of a good story.

00:13.760 --> 00:16.200
Someone, somewhere,
somehow got creative.

00:16.360 --> 00:17.520
Holy shit.

00:17.600 --> 00:19.920
Who's the asshole who
ruined NorBAC's reputation?

00:20.200 --> 00:21.280
Wasn't me.

00:21.400 --> 00:23.800
Who was it 'cause that's where
I'm going next with a baseball bat.

00:24.160 --> 00:26.040
I didn't send him to Florida, David.

00:26.120 --> 00:28.000
I don't know
what you're talking about.

00:28.200 --> 00:30.440
Charringa knew there was
a fastidiosa bug on the way

00:30.520 --> 00:32.240
so he decided to do
a pre-emptive vaccination

00:32.400 --> 00:34.080
on his orange groves in Florida.

00:34.200 --> 00:36.280
- Okay, wait a minute. He had a vaccine?
- Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:36.360 --> 00:38.760
No, these people have
been using an engineered version

00:38.880 --> 00:41.880
of fastidiosa as a vaccination on
their grapes in California for 3 years.

00:42.160 --> 00:44.360
You think Charringa did this to himself?

00:44.480 --> 00:45.880
I don't think, I know.

00:47.160 --> 00:48.280
Owen.

00:48.560 --> 00:49.840
What are you doing here?

00:49.920 --> 00:51.800
I got rid of the weed, and now,

00:51.960 --> 00:54.120
the 2 guys who own the weed,
well, they want to kill me.

00:54.200 --> 00:55.200
- What?
- Who?

00:55.520 --> 00:57.720
Look, I just need
a place for a bit.

00:58.080 --> 00:59.000
LET ME DIE

00:59.160 --> 01:01.440
It's a decision
he's had a lot of time to make.

01:02.520 --> 01:03.720
Glenn...

01:04.720 --> 01:06.080
we're running.

01:06.160 --> 01:07.320
And...

01:08.640 --> 01:10.880
feel the leaves under our feet.

01:13.240 --> 01:15.360
We're in a forest.

01:15.880 --> 01:17.520
We're just going

01:17.920 --> 01:21.800
so fast now that
the wind is pinching our ears.

01:22.000 --> 01:23.520
And...

01:23.760 --> 01:26.160
and our eyes are watering.

01:27.200 --> 01:29.720
We can't even feel our cheeks anymore.

01:30.320 --> 01:31.640
Look up ahead.

01:31.880 --> 01:33.240
There's a...

01:33.600 --> 01:34.720
There's a...

01:37.080 --> 01:38.560
There's a meadow.

01:41.800 --> 01:43.160
Can you see it?

01:45.960 --> 01:48.000
Oh, now you can run.

01:50.000 --> 01:56.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:14.240 --> 02:15.080
What?

02:15.160 --> 02:17.200
Excuse me, sir,
would you mind turning off your engine?

02:17.320 --> 02:18.720
- What?
- You're idling.

02:18.960 --> 02:20.600
Yeah. Thanks, officer.

02:20.920 --> 02:23.960
Are you aware that greenhouse gases
caused by the burning of fossil fuels

02:24.120 --> 02:26.240
and biomasses are contributing
to atmospheric brown clouds

02:26.320 --> 02:28.440
that already threaten millions
of people all over the world?

02:29.440 --> 02:30.760
Looks pretty good to me.

02:30.840 --> 02:33.360
Sir, at this very moment,
a cloud of enormous proportions

02:33.560 --> 02:35.120
is heading towards Mexico City

02:35.440 --> 02:37.960
due to its unique
geographical location.

02:38.480 --> 02:39.440
No shit.

02:39.520 --> 02:41.200
The cloud is being made
worse by greenhouse gases,

02:41.320 --> 02:43.200
such as the ones
emanating from your tailpipe.

02:43.360 --> 02:45.480
So, my tailpipe is
messing up Mexico City?

02:45.560 --> 02:48.240
Yes. Furthermore,
tremors have been detected

02:48.440 --> 02:50.200
in the nearby
Popocatepetl Mountain.

03:07.000 --> 03:08.120
Carlos.

03:08.640 --> 03:10.200
Ah, this is it?

03:10.280 --> 03:12.160
Caroline will fill you in.
She's up in her office.

03:12.440 --> 03:13.720
Okay, I will get David.

03:17.440 --> 03:18.680
- David.
- Hmm?

03:18.840 --> 03:19.920
It's here.

03:20.080 --> 03:22.000
Any idea what this is all about?
What's in here?

03:22.080 --> 03:23.200
No idea.

03:23.840 --> 03:24.760
Good morning.

03:24.840 --> 03:26.000
- Good morning.
- Good morning.

03:26.600 --> 03:28.120
How're things going with Owen?

03:28.200 --> 03:30.440
Uh... You mean is he still around?

03:31.120 --> 03:33.200
Yup, he's still around.

04:59.520 --> 05:02.400
2.08 - Haze

05:03.000 --> 05:05.280
Owen? Is that the kid
from the subway?

05:05.360 --> 05:08.080
Yeah. Showed up at my place.
Cold, hungry, and broke.

05:08.320 --> 05:09.960
I told him to go away.

05:10.280 --> 05:12.280
- You're so good with kids...
- Aren't I?

05:22.800 --> 05:24.760
She usually doesn't lock it.

05:25.000 --> 05:26.120
Caroline?

05:26.280 --> 05:27.640
Just a minute.

05:33.720 --> 05:35.440
Oh. Just arrived?

05:35.640 --> 05:37.240
Yeah. Couple of minutes ago.

05:38.680 --> 05:41.200
- You not gonna lock it, are ya?
- Didn't realize I had.

05:48.080 --> 05:50.120
So, what are we looking at?

05:50.600 --> 05:53.800
Homeland Security has been
keeping a close watch on 2 brothers.

05:53.960 --> 05:55.080
Scientists.

05:55.440 --> 05:57.640
Stefan and Vincent Manford.

05:59.720 --> 06:01.320
Any particular reason?

06:01.440 --> 06:04.360
They've been ordering viral DNA
for their lab in Chicago.

06:04.520 --> 06:06.680
- Private lab?
- Yes. Just the 2 of them.

06:06.920 --> 06:09.160
So they've been ordering
viral DNA. So what?

06:09.320 --> 06:11.720
That's what you need
if you're studying viruses, Caroline.

06:11.840 --> 06:13.440
There's more, David.

06:18.880 --> 06:20.880
Oh, how nice.
From Homeland Security,

06:20.960 --> 06:22.840
for all the good work
we've done, no doubt.

06:22.920 --> 06:26.760
No, the Manford brothers sent this
to the President of the United States.

06:27.040 --> 06:28.400
- Big fans?
- Not at all.

06:28.520 --> 06:30.320
They've been very verbal
about how much they dislike

06:30.400 --> 06:32.520
the way the President's
been handling U.S. affairs.

06:32.680 --> 06:34.320
Them and 75% of
the rest of the world.

06:34.400 --> 06:36.760
That's what got them on
Homeland Security's watch list.

06:36.960 --> 06:38.640
Whatever happened to
your constitutional right

06:38.800 --> 06:40.520
to speak out against your government?

06:40.640 --> 06:43.000
You can but if you're buying
viral DNA at the same time

06:43.120 --> 06:44.760
you end up on Homeland's radar.

06:45.280 --> 06:47.720
They're thinking these brothers
are involved in bioterrorism.

06:47.840 --> 06:49.880
Oh, let's just say,
they're not taking any chances.

06:50.560 --> 06:52.560
So Washington ran their own test.

06:54.040 --> 06:55.800
Looks like they took a little nip.

06:55.880 --> 06:58.880
They tested 250 milliliters.
They didn't find anything.

06:59.120 --> 07:01.520
- So what do they want us to do?
- They want us to confirm

07:01.600 --> 07:03.560
that there's just
Cabernet Sauvignon in the bottle.

07:03.680 --> 07:05.120
Pop the cork,
let's have a tasting party.

07:05.320 --> 07:08.040
Oh, cut the goddamn sarcasm,
David, and get to it.

07:08.280 --> 07:09.520
Absolutely, your Worship.

07:09.600 --> 07:11.280
Is there anything else
I can do for you today?

07:11.360 --> 07:13.360
- Maybe a foot massage?
- Just test the bottle,

07:13.480 --> 07:16.320
and then you're... No, we are going
to Chicago to take a look at their lab.

07:16.520 --> 07:19.200
- Take a look at their lab?
- I have my orders, David.

07:19.400 --> 07:22.000
Orders! Since when
did we join the fucking army?

07:22.160 --> 07:24.440
Orders. Jesus, this is bullshit!

07:29.720 --> 07:32.160
- Are you okay, Caroline?
- Yeah. I'm fine, I'm just tired.

07:32.880 --> 07:34.480
You've had a tough week?

07:35.760 --> 07:36.960
Yeah.

07:40.400 --> 07:42.000
We'll get right on this.

07:44.200 --> 07:46.120
Thank you, Carlos.

07:53.560 --> 07:56.200
Got 3 bull's-eyes and a pigeon.
You want a game?

07:56.520 --> 07:57.600
No.

07:59.200 --> 08:01.520
You know, this is
a difficult time for her.

08:01.760 --> 08:03.880
You know, it's a difficult time
for all of us, Carlos.

08:04.040 --> 08:06.800
Ok, I'm sorry about her nephew...
Glenn. I'm sorry about Glenn.

08:07.160 --> 08:09.360
I'm sorry I had to hear about it
second-goddamn-hand from Bob.

08:09.800 --> 08:11.200
She kept it very personal.

08:11.280 --> 08:14.280
She should keep her nervous breakdown
personal, too and not take it out on me, then.

08:14.560 --> 08:15.920
I just think if you were a little bit--

08:16.040 --> 08:18.480
Just do what the lady says
and check everything ok?

08:18.640 --> 08:20.680
The bottle, the wine,
the cork, the label,

08:20.840 --> 08:21.800
the fucking glue on the label,

08:21.880 --> 08:23.640
we'll bring in a wine expert,
find out where the grapes were from.

08:23.800 --> 08:24.960
Wine experts get it wrong
more often than not.

08:25.120 --> 08:27.080
Whatever, just go up
one side of it, down the other

08:27.120 --> 08:29.560
and leave the report in my underwear
drawer. I'll find it someday.

08:32.400 --> 08:33.400
What?

08:34.600 --> 08:35.960
I'll get on it.

09:07.720 --> 09:09.800
- Morning.
- Morning.

09:11.000 --> 09:12.520
Why are you doing that?

09:13.560 --> 09:15.200
I heard about Glenn.

09:15.680 --> 09:17.240
Bob, I'm sorry.

09:17.600 --> 09:18.800
The cloud.

09:22.360 --> 09:24.080
It's still moving, Bob.

09:24.320 --> 09:26.920
- Are these the latest NOAA maps.
- Hmm-hmm. Just came in.

09:27.480 --> 09:29.360
See, it's closer.
The western-most tendril

09:29.440 --> 09:32.240
is already touching the coast.
It travelled a 100 kilometers overnight.

09:32.320 --> 09:33.880
I put together
a program of my own

09:33.960 --> 09:37.600
that downloads data from
the National Weather Service.

09:37.680 --> 09:39.680
So we've got NEXRAD radar,
air quality, satellite views,

09:39.880 --> 09:42.240
- speed, altitude...
- It's only at 5400 meters high?

09:42.400 --> 09:44.280
Down from 6500
before it hit the coast.

09:44.480 --> 09:47.360
We have to watch that if it goes down
any more... How fast is it moving?

09:47.760 --> 09:48.840
Well it varies.

09:48.920 --> 09:51.440
Satellite had it going as fast
as 55 kilometers an hour

09:51.640 --> 09:54.760
and then at a dead stop.
Right now, it's at 23 K.

09:54.880 --> 09:56.120
But still heading toward
Mexico City. Right?

09:56.200 --> 09:58.440
The NOAA hasn't given me
any models as to where it's going.

09:58.560 --> 10:01.040
Yeah, but looking at it.
It's heading toward Mexico City.

10:01.200 --> 10:02.760
I know, but Bob,
I'm not a climatologist.

10:02.880 --> 10:04.400
I know. I know.

10:04.760 --> 10:05.880
What about the mountain?

10:06.640 --> 10:08.400
The mountain, yeah.

10:09.240 --> 10:10.160
Here.

10:11.040 --> 10:13.400
- It just started this morning.
- It's happening.

10:13.720 --> 10:15.960
<i>It seems, yeah.
The Instituto Seismologico</i>

10:16.120 --> 10:19.400
is predicting a constant eruption
of gases over the next 24 to 36 hours...

10:19.640 --> 10:21.640
What are they doing?
Have they posted smog alerts?

10:21.720 --> 10:24.480
- Have they shut down the major industries?
- Posted alerts yes.

10:24.680 --> 10:27.520
But getting 18 million people

10:27.600 --> 10:30.320
- to respond isn't exactly...
- We need to get David on this.

10:30.440 --> 10:31.840
I have to show him this.

10:32.080 --> 10:33.600
Please, can you print it?

10:33.960 --> 10:35.200
I'll be at my desk.

10:36.760 --> 10:37.560
OK.

10:42.880 --> 10:43.960
Did David talk to you

10:44.760 --> 10:47.040
- about Owen?
- Not really.

10:47.800 --> 10:49.840
I told him he had to help him.

10:50.040 --> 10:51.080
Ah.

10:51.480 --> 10:53.720
I mean, he couldn't just
throw him out in the street, right?

10:53.880 --> 10:54.640
No.

10:55.000 --> 10:57.320
I think he's pissed off
at me for saying that.

10:58.960 --> 11:00.800
Why don't you talk to David about it?

11:02.280 --> 11:04.400
I guess I could talk to David.

11:07.680 --> 11:09.920
OK. I'll have to do a full run on these.

11:10.120 --> 11:10.880
OK.

11:11.760 --> 11:14.600
Now, you just want
a viral gene chip on the wine, right?

11:14.720 --> 11:16.720
- Check for all known bacteria.
- You got it.

11:46.280 --> 11:47.840
If you're going
to start giving me "orders",

11:48.000 --> 11:50.000
you can do a little goddamn respect!

11:50.160 --> 11:52.360
and not like I'm some
kind of ass kissing subordinate!

11:52.600 --> 11:54.640
You always talk
to yourself like that?

11:55.160 --> 11:56.520
What the hell are you doing here?

11:56.640 --> 11:58.400
Let me in and I'll fill you in.

12:05.760 --> 12:06.920
How'd you get around back?

12:07.040 --> 12:09.720
It was easy. I mean,
a bit harder than Canadian Customs.

12:09.880 --> 12:11.600
Owen, I'm kind of busy right now.

12:11.840 --> 12:14.680
- Yeah, yeah, you look super busy.
- You need some money?

12:15.880 --> 12:18.120
No, I just stopped by
because I need some advice.

12:18.280 --> 12:20.560
Not from me, man.
I suck at advice.

12:22.440 --> 12:25.160
Look, David, I don't have
anybody else to talk to.

12:25.520 --> 12:28.040
And I mean, it appears
that you listen to me.

12:28.160 --> 12:29.160
Yeah, well...

12:29.360 --> 12:31.200
- I can't go back.
- Sure you can.

12:31.360 --> 12:33.640
I'll get you a bus ticket,
I'll get you a plane ticket.

12:34.080 --> 12:36.320
Going back to New York
is a good thing.

12:36.440 --> 12:38.960
- You'd be with your people.
- You don't understand.

12:39.120 --> 12:40.480
They'll fucking stick me.

12:41.000 --> 12:42.080
I dumped their dope.

12:42.200 --> 12:44.640
And that shit was worth, like,
half a million bucks on the street.

12:45.040 --> 12:47.720
It's good, because Sunshine
and everybody, they got better.

12:48.960 --> 12:51.040
David, I have something to
show you if you have the...

12:51.600 --> 12:52.760
Hey, Owen. What are you?

12:52.880 --> 12:54.200
- Where did you?
- What is it, Bob?

12:54.280 --> 12:57.080
Emissions from cars and factories,
trapped by the inversion layer,

12:57.160 --> 12:58.520
combined with the mass of pollution

12:58.600 --> 13:00.160
moving across the Pacific complicated

13:00.240 --> 13:02.200
by the gases emitting out
of Mount Popocatepetl.

13:02.720 --> 13:05.120
Theoretically, David,
we could be heading towards

13:05.320 --> 13:06.920
a perfect pollution storm
over Mexico City.

13:07.000 --> 13:08.480
What the hell
do you guys do here?

13:08.640 --> 13:11.560
OK, well you know the procedure.
Tell Caroline to contact Mexico

13:11.640 --> 13:13.520
and find out what
their story is and... What?

13:13.680 --> 13:15.600
- Mexico City is on the line.
- What?

13:15.680 --> 13:17.400
I need you on this call.
I need to convince them

13:17.560 --> 13:19.280
- that this disaster could happen.
- I can't help you here, Bob.

13:19.400 --> 13:21.120
- I'm not up to speed...
- David, please!

13:21.360 --> 13:23.200
Okay, all right.

13:23.360 --> 13:25.720
Get Carlos in on this,
I'll be down in a second.

13:26.160 --> 13:27.200
Excuse me.

13:28.800 --> 13:29.680
Look, Owen,

13:29.840 --> 13:33.200
I got a thing and
just go get yourself a...

13:33.600 --> 13:36.400
you know, a hat, and some lunch.
We'll talk later.

13:36.640 --> 13:37.920
Should I go back to your place?

13:38.080 --> 13:40.120
Yeah. Clean the toilets
if you don't mind.

13:40.440 --> 13:41.600
Yeah, thanks.

13:41.920 --> 13:42.920
Oh, Owen.

13:43.000 --> 13:45.800
If you can just, you know,
let yourself out the way you came in.

13:53.560 --> 13:55.960
This is where the NOAA and
other international weather agencies

13:56.040 --> 13:57.120
had it one week ago.

13:58.280 --> 13:59.200
All right.

13:59.320 --> 14:00.800
This is 3 days ago.

14:01.840 --> 14:03.160
Less than 3 hours ago.

14:09.360 --> 14:11.040
They're aware of the cloud...

14:11.120 --> 14:12.840
They don't think
it's going to be a problem.

14:12.960 --> 14:14.320
Well, alone it wouldn't be a problem.

14:14.440 --> 14:16.280
But it will still would be
unhealthy. And in combination

14:16.440 --> 14:19.080
with the gases emitting from the
mountain and the intense inversion layer

14:19.200 --> 14:22.520
over Mexico City, I believe they
can produce a very intense acid rain.

14:23.000 --> 14:25.120
Excuse me. Acid rain?

14:25.240 --> 14:27.080
- Specifically sulfuric acid.
- Sulfuric?

14:27.320 --> 14:28.840
You have data to support this?

14:28.920 --> 14:30.600
Right now it's purely theoretical but I...

14:30.680 --> 14:32.960
Based on this theoretical scenario,

14:33.200 --> 14:34.760
what is it
that you want us to do?

14:34.880 --> 14:36.240
Well, I thought that...

14:36.320 --> 14:38.360
This is a potentially very dangerous...

14:38.560 --> 14:39.880
People could die.

14:40.240 --> 14:42.640
This is a very toxic rain
that could destroy....

14:42.760 --> 14:44.000
It's got a destructive power.

14:44.120 --> 14:46.720
I think what Dr. Melnikov
is suggesting is that you need

14:46.840 --> 14:49.000
to intensify your efforts
to reduce emissions

14:49.080 --> 14:51.120
in your industry and
your transportation.

14:51.240 --> 14:53.960
Dr. Melnikov,
are you a climatologist?

14:54.040 --> 14:55.280
Biochemist, biophysicist.

14:55.400 --> 14:57.440
We've been consulting with
the NOAA and their climatologists.

14:57.640 --> 14:59.600
- And they agree with you?
- Not yet they're still...

14:59.720 --> 15:02.160
Dr. Melnikov, I am a climatologist.

15:02.800 --> 15:05.840
Are you familiar with the weather
patterns of central and southern Mexico?

15:05.920 --> 15:08.040
- To some degree.
- Wind patterns?

15:08.560 --> 15:09.160
No.

15:09.280 --> 15:11.840
So wind patterns have not
been formulated into your theory?

15:12.520 --> 15:14.120
My theory is based on the data.

15:14.280 --> 15:16.200
The mountain gases combining with...

15:24.280 --> 15:26.440
They think we're overstating our case.

15:28.880 --> 15:31.680
No, listen. Even if
the jet stream were to blow through

15:31.760 --> 15:34.000
I don't think that would make a difference
The inversion layer is too low.

15:34.240 --> 15:36.000
The emissions
from the mountain are trapped.

15:36.080 --> 15:37.360
- Bob.
- Fine!

15:38.160 --> 15:39.600
Then I'll just prove it.
But believe me.

15:39.720 --> 15:42.880
You've got to do something about it. Cut the
emissions or it won't be a theory much longer.

15:44.800 --> 15:46.600
Oh, Christ.

15:48.640 --> 15:49.640
Bob.

15:50.040 --> 15:51.160
Bob!

15:51.480 --> 15:53.080
You just made the
call too soon, Bob.

15:53.200 --> 15:55.320
No David, too late.
They're not seeing what can happen.

15:55.440 --> 15:57.200
- Could happen.
- No. I can show them exactly

15:57.280 --> 15:59.200
what can happen if everything
collides over Mexico City...

15:59.280 --> 16:00.800
- Then show them.
- Why don't they listen?

16:00.880 --> 16:03.560
Just Bob, do the science.
Show them.

16:04.960 --> 16:06.320
OK, David.

16:06.520 --> 16:08.000
I'll do the science.

16:11.360 --> 16:12.360
David.

16:16.920 --> 16:19.040
Oh, why do I have to watch this?

16:19.240 --> 16:22.360
Because Caroline thinks that it will give
you some perspective on the brothers.

16:22.560 --> 16:24.360
So that you know what
you're dealing with.

16:25.720 --> 16:28.000
<i>- Why don't you sit down?
- I'd rather stand.</i>

16:29.520 --> 16:32.520
That is Stefan Manford, age 30.

16:32.760 --> 16:36.080
He has a Ph.D. in Molecular Biology
from the University of Chicago.

16:36.480 --> 16:39.240
He does most of the talking.
The other one is his brother Vincent.

16:39.400 --> 16:42.560
34. Also has a Ph.D.
in Molecular Biology.

16:42.760 --> 16:45.280
- Also from the University of Chicago.
- Who's the suit?

16:45.360 --> 16:48.440
Lew Austiger. He oversees
the Midwest operations.

16:48.600 --> 16:50.600
<i>Can you explain to me
why you've been looking</i>

16:50.720 --> 16:52.760
<i>into various strains of viral DNA?</i>

16:53.160 --> 16:55.800
<i>- How else would we study a virus?
- Good answer.</i>

16:55.960 --> 16:58.360
<i>What exactly does that mean?
- Dumb question.</i>

16:58.720 --> 17:00.560
Well, Mr Austiger,
first we're going to need

17:00.720 --> 17:03.000
to explain to you a couple
of things about viral DNA.

17:03.160 --> 17:06.200
Yeah, no kidding.
Lew doesn't have a clue.

